This introduction serves as a guide to the primary concepts of the R
language. First off, make sure you have installed
[R](https://www.r-project.org/) and [RStudio](https://www.rstudio.com/).
You can do everything presented here in R, but RStudio provides a nice
interface with added functionality.

#### Base R looks like this:

![](data:image/png;base64,)
![](data:image/png;base64,)

The top image is the console, where your R code is executed and the
results are displayed. It is possible to type commands directly into the
console window. However, it is better to have all of your R code saved
in a script. The bottom image is an R script (save it with extension
.R).

#### RStudio IDE looks like this:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

In RStudio, the console (bottom left) and scrpit (top left) windows are
combined, and added functionality is displayed in the right pane. Note
that there are also tabs for multiple scripts, which is very handy. In
the bottom right pane you see tabs for Environment, History, Plots,
Packages, Help and Viewer. I use the Plots and Help tabs most
frequently. The top right pane shows a directory structure and files for
easy access. RStudio is highly customizable. I have changed the colour
of my console and script from the default. There are several colour
options in RStudio -\>Preferences -\>Appearance. There are also many
great RStudio resources, including a set of [cheatsheets and reference
guides](https://www.rstudio.com/resources/cheatsheets/) that are useful
when new to R and RStudio.

To create a new R script you can either go to File -\> New File -\> R
Script, or click on the icon with the "+" sign in the top left of the
RStudio window and select R Script. If you like keyboard shortcuts, use
Command+Shift+N in MacOS (Ctrl+Shift+N in Windows). In order to execute
lines of code saved in a script, you can highlight the line(s) you wish
to run and then press the "Run" icon on the top right of your script
window, or you can highlight the line(s) and use the keyboard shortcut
Command+Return in MacOS (Ctrl+Enter in Windows).

Now we will go through a set of commands to learn basic R functionality.
I recommend that you save them in an R script for future use, but you
may also just copy and paste them directly into the console and press
Return (Enter).

#### Using R as a Calculator

(note \# is a comment in R)

```r
# Simple operations + - * / ^
4+5 # addition
4-5 # subtraction
4*5 # multiplication
4/5 # division
4^5 # power
# Mathematical operations
sqrt(4) # square root
log(4) # natural log
log10(4) # log base 10
exp(4) # exponential
4%%5 # modulus
4%/% # integer division
```

#### Assignment Operator

There are two ways to make assignments in R, using `<-` or `=`

```r
x<-200
x=200 # equivalent to above with <-
# look at assigned object
x
```

```r
# you don't have to assign to a single letter name, and you can assign the results of an operation
seven<-5+2
seven
```

    [1] 7

When storing more than one number to your object, combine numbers using
`c()`. Inside the parentheses, include numbers separated by a comma. For
example, we create two vectors of numbers (these vectors can also be
called variables).

```r
v1<-c(4,10,3,2,12)
v2<-c(1,2,3,4,5)
v1
```

    [1]  4 10  3  2 12

#### Different Ways to Create Vectors
In addition to specifying specific numbers and combining them together
into a vector using `c`, we can create vectors of sequences or ranges of
numbers with `seq()`, `rep()`, and `:`. Try the following:

```r
# a sequence of numbers from 2 to 10 by increments of 2
s<-seq(2,14, by=2) 
# repeat the number 5 20 times
t<-rep(5,20)
# a range of numbers from 1 to 5
u<-1:5
```

#### Operations on Vectors

We can apply simple and more complicated mathematical operations to
numbers and data vectors. For example `v1+x` will return a vector with
200 added to each value of variable1. Try these vector operations:

```r
v1+v2
v3<-v1/v2
```

Be careful about your vector lengths. For example, the operation
variable1\*t cannot be performed because the vectors are different in
length (variable has 5 elements and t has 7 elements).

#### Creating Matrices

Vectors can be combined into matrices using `c()` (combine), `rbind()`
(row bind) and `cbind()` (column bind). Combining vectors with `c` will
stack vectors in the same row, creating a concatenated vector. Combining
two vectors with `rbind()` will create a matrix with two rows and n
columns, where n is the length of the vectors. Combining two vectors
with `cbind()` will create a matrix with two columns and n rows. Again,
we must be careful about vector lengths and matrix dimensions when
combining.

```r
c(variable1,variable2)
matrix1<-rbind(v1,v2)
matrix2<-cbind(v1,v2)
```

#### Creating Data Frames

We can create a dataset from two (or more) variables using the
`data.frame` command:

```r
dat<-data.frame(v1,v2)
```

Note how dat is similar to matrix2 (column binding is similar to
creating a data frame). The distinction between the two is the type of
object that they are (matrix versus data.frame), and the subsequent
properties they have. If there is any question as to whether an object
is a matrix or a data frame you can use is.matrix() or is.data.frame()
to check. A boolean value will be returned.

```r
is.matrix(dat)
```

    [1] FALSE

```r
is.data.frame(dat)
```

    [1] TRUE

#### Importing Data from External Files

We can read in an external dataset with a variety of `read` commands,
including `read.table`, `read.csv` or `read.delim`. In general you can
use `read.table` and specify whether there is a `header=FALSE` or
`header=TRUE`, and the delimiter with `sep=""` (where you put , for
comma separated, for tab separated, or a blank space for space separated
delimiters). For comma separated data, `read.csv` is a better option as
you do not need to specify the delimiter or header (it is assumed that
there is a header). Some examples using [these
data](https://github.com/meredithfranklin/meredithfranklin.github.io/tree/master/data)
on jogging distance and duration. Note, be sure to specify the path to
wherever you saved the file to be imported.

```r
# tab delimited
jogging.txt<-read.table("sample_data_jogging.txt", header=TRUE, sep='\t')
# comma separated
jogging<-read.csv("sample_data_jogging.csv")
```

#### Working with Data Frames

Since R is a vector/matrix based language, all data frames are stored so
that they may be referenced by row and column of a matrix. Furthermore
the contents of datasets, imported from an external file or created in
R, can be examined using commands including `summary` to get summary
statistics of the entire contents of the dataset, `names` to get the
column headers of the dataset, and `dim` to get the dimensions of the
dataset.

```r
summary(jogging) 
```

       subject_id     jog_time_hrs   jog_distance_mi
     Min.   : 1.00   Min.   :0.500   Min.   : 3.00  
     1st Qu.: 3.25   1st Qu.:1.250   1st Qu.: 5.50  
     Median : 5.50   Median :2.250   Median :11.00  
     Mean   : 5.50   Mean   :2.400   Mean   :11.50  
     3rd Qu.: 7.75   3rd Qu.:3.375   3rd Qu.:14.75  
     Max.   :10.00   Max.   :5.000   Max.   :26.00  

```r
names(jogging) 
```

    [1] "subject_id"      "jog_time_hrs"    "jog_distance_mi"

```r
dim(jogging) 
```

    [1] 10  3

We see that there are 10 rows and 4 columns in the dataset. To extract
one column, or a variable from our dataset, use `$`:

```r
jogging$subject_id 
```

Adding a column is done in a similar fashion, but by assignment. Below
we calculate jogging speed from distance/time and add this as a column
to the jogging data frame.

```r
jogging$jog_speed_mph<-jogging$jog_distance_mi/jogging$jog_time_hrs
```

Since data are stored as matrices, we can also look at data in terms of
specifying the row and/or column number in the form
dataset\[row,column\].

```r
jogging[1,] # get 1st row
jogging[,2] # get 2nd column
jogging[2,3] # get observation in row 2, column 3
```

We can also use the dataset to create other datasets. For instance, if
we have duplicate rows that we wish to remove from our dataset, we can
use the function `duplicated`. By referencing only the rows from
dataset\[row,column\] for duplicated values, we will keep all original
columns in the dataset, but will remove duplicated rows.

```r
jogging.nodups<-jogging[!duplicated(jogging),]
```

Missing values are referenced as `NA` in R. If we had missing values in
our dataset and wish to remove these rows, we can apply the function
`complete.cases` in a similar fashion as we applied duplicated above.

```r
jogging.nomiss<-jogging[complete.cases(jogging),]
```

#### Writing Data to an External File

After we have done calculations and added new columns to our data frame,
we might like to save it as a .csv or .txt file. In these situations we
need to use `write.table()` or `write.csv()` specifying the data frame
to be written and the file name (with path) to write to. For
`write.table()` we also must specify the delimiter. R automatically adds
a row id, which I don't find particularly useful, so also include the
option `row.names=FALSE` when saving to external files.

```r
write.table(jogging,'jogging_new.txt', sep="\t",row.names=FALSE)
write.csv(jogging,'jogging_new.csv',row.names=FALSE)
```

Alternatively, if we will be using our data in R again, we may wish to
save it as an R dataset .Rdata. For this we use `save()`.

```r
save(jogging, file='jogging_new.RData')
```

#### Lists

In addition to vectors, matrices and data frames, you can store data in
lists. Basically an R list is a vector of objects. The nice thing about
lists is that each of your objects in the list can be of different
length or dimension. For example, we can combine a scalar, vector and
matrix that we created above into a list:

```r
x<-200
y<-rep(5,20)
matrix1<-rbind(v1,v2)
myList<-list(x,y,matrix1)
```

We can extract elements of a list with single square brackets `[]`. For
instance `myList[3]` will return the `matrix1` portion of `myList`. We
can extract multiple members of a list by referencing with `c` inside
the call to the list. For example, to extract the 2nd and 3nd elements
of `myList` use `myList[c(3,2)]`. We can extract a single observation
from an element of a list by referencing it with a second square
bracket, `myList[[3]][2,]` will return the second row from the third
element of the list. Note here, that if you have a matrix or data.frame
in your list that you reference it in matrix form `[row,col]`. Also note
that we have to include the double square bracket to first extract the
element from the list. To add another layer of complexity to lists, it
is also possible to have 'named' lists.

#### Other Useful Commands

If you will be working out of one directory, namely reading and writing
files into one folder, it is handy to set your working directory using
`setwd("\user\path\")` so you don't have to re-write it every time you
want to access an external file.

We haven't used any R packages yet, but we will need some in future
tutorials. In RStudio, you can use the drop down menu under
Tools-\>Install Packages to install a local file (.zip, .gz) or browse
the CRAN repository. If you know what package you wish to install, a
simpler way is to enter `install.packages("packagename")` into the
console.

If you need more information about any particular function, R provides
extensive documentation that is accessible through `?` or `help()` (e.g.
`?read.table`). If you are unsure of the exact function name, a fuzzy
search using `apropos()` will return a list of functions with variations
of the search name (e.g.?`apropos("matrix")`).
